<DOC><DOCNO> AP891121-0163 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-89 2030EST</FILEID><FIRST>r w AM-Pentagon-Missiles     11-21 0228</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Pentagon-Missiles,230</SECOND><HEAD>Defense Department Attempts Missile Technology Controls</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Pentagon announced on Tuesday it took twosteps to help control the spread of ballistic missile technology,including tightening oversight of foreign and domesticmanufacturers of missile parts that deal with the Department ofDefense.   The actions are designed to help curb the export of sensitivemissile technologies to nations such as Iraq, said one Pentagonofficial, who spoke on condition he not be named.   Under the new procedures, the Defense Department will nowrequire domestic and foreign contracting companies to comply withthe laws and regulations of their own government in regard tomissile-related export controls, as well as those of the UnitedStates.   In addition, the department will establish procedures to ensurethat its cooperative defense programs are in compliance withMissile Technology Control Regime, a 10-nation agreement amongWestern nations to curb the spread of dangerous missiles.   ``This means we can put pressure on the contractors, foreign anddomestic. It gives us more leverage. We'll have the authority nowto look at what business they do with other nations, and if wedon't like it, we won't do business with them,'' the source said.   ``At a minimum, these initiatives will encourage DODcontractors, including their subsidiaries, to act responsibly inmissile related exports,'' the Pentagon said in a statementannouncing the steps.</TEXT></DOC>